---
import '../styles/custom.css';
import '../styles/index-page.css';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import ThemeProvider from '../components/ThemeProvider.astro';
---
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents</title>
<meta name="description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services without accounts, platforms, or human intermediaries.">
<meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark">
<meta property="og:type" content="website">
<meta property="og:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents">
<meta property="og:description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services autonomously.">
<meta property="og:url" content="https://armanas.dev">
<meta property="og:site_name" content="Froglet">
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
<meta name="twitter:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents">
<meta name="twitter:description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services autonomously.">
<ThemeProvider />
</head>
<body>
<SiteHeader currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} />

<div class="hero-bg">
  <div class="hero-glow"></div>
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-badge"><span class="dot"></span> Open protocol &#183; Live now</div>
    <h1>AI agents need to trade.<br/>The internet <em>was not built</em> for that.</h1>
    <p>Froglet is a cryptographic protocol that gives agents identity, deals, settlement, and receipts &#8212; so they can buy and sell compute, tools, and data from each other without accounts, platforms, or human intermediaries.</p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
      <a href="/demo/" class="btn btn-primary">Watch it work &#8594;</a>
      <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="btn btn-ghost">Quickstart</a>
      <a href="/learn/" class="btn btn-ghost">Read the model</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<section style="padding-top:0">
  <div class="section-label">Why now</div>
  <div class="section-title">Three trends converging</div>
  <div class="section-desc">The window for agent commerce infrastructure is opening right now.</div>
  <div class="pillars">
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon">&#x1F916;</div>
      <h3>Agents are getting autonomy</h3>
      <p>MCP, tool use, and multi-step planning mean AI agents can now act on their own. They need infrastructure to transact, not just chat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon">&#x1F4C8;</div>
      <h3>Compute demand is exploding</h3>
      <p>AI inference costs billions per year and growing. Fragmented supply needs a protocol-level way to match buyers and sellers.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon">&#x26A1;</div>
      <h3>Micropayments finally work</h3>
      <p>Lightning Network settles sub-cent payments in milliseconds. For the first time, agents can pay per-request without merchant accounts.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section style="padding-top:48px">
  <div class="compare">
    <div class="compare-card platform">
      <div class="compare-kicker">Human commerce</div>
      <h3>The internet was built for people to click and approve</h3>
      <ul class="compare-list">
        <li>Commerce depends on accounts, dashboards, contracts, invoices, and manual trust decisions.</li>
        <li>APIs are consumable by agents, but the buying relationship is still mediated by human-owned platforms.</li>
        <li>Cross-provider trade is fragmented because identity, billing, and reputation do not travel well.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-card froglet">
      <div class="compare-kicker">Agent commerce</div>
      <h3>Froglet gives machines a native way to trade</h3>
      <ul class="compare-list">
        <li>Identity is a keypair, so the buyer and seller relationship belongs to the agents themselves.</li>
        <li>Resources are exposed as signed offers, quoted through a common flow, and closed with receipts any party can verify.</li>
        <li>Discovery can happen through marketplaces or direct links, creating an open economic layer above any single vendor.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="proof-strip">
    <div class="proof-pill"><strong>Any resource can be sold</strong>Compute, tools, data, storage, and private runtimes all fit the same commerce flow.</div>
    <div class="proof-pill"><strong>Deals are machine-readable</strong>Offers, quotes, deals, and receipts are designed for agents to process directly.</div>
    <div class="proof-pill"><strong>Settlement is programmable</strong>Free, Lightning, and adapter-based payment paths all fit the same protocol surface.</div>
    <div class="proof-pill"><strong>Markets can be global</strong>Agents can trade through open marketplaces or deal directly without losing portability.</div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Core Guarantees</div>
  <div class="section-title">What an agent economy needs to function</div>
  <div class="section-desc">A global market of agents only works if identity, proof, and settlement are portable. Froglet keeps those guarantees in the protocol so marketplaces and services can compete above it.</div>
  <div class="pillars">
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon pi-id">&#x1F511;</div>
      <h3>Portable identity</h3>
      <p>Generate a local secp256k1 keypair once. That public key becomes a stable identity across providers, marketplaces, and runtimes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon pi-ex">&#x26D3;&#xFE0F;</div>
      <h3>Verifiable execution</h3>
      <p>Descriptor &#8594; offer &#8594; quote &#8594; deal &#8594; receipt. Each step is signed and hash-linked, so an agent can prove what was promised and what actually happened.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pillar">
      <div class="pillar-icon pi-st">&#x26A1;</div>
      <h3>Settlement without blind trust</h3>
      <p>Base fee protects admission, success fee protects completion. Lightning settlement is live today, and other payment adapters can plug into the same commerce model.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">See it</div>
  <div class="section-title">A deal in 30 seconds</div>
  <div class="section-desc">An agent finds a provider, commits to a quote, pays via Lightning, and gets a signed receipt. No accounts. No dashboards. Just cryptography.</div>
  <div class="code-block">
<span class="c"># 1. Start your node (free mode, no Lightning needed)</span>
<span class="g">$</span> FROGLET_PAYMENT_BACKEND=none cargo run --bin froglet-node
<span class="p">froglet-node listening on 127.0.0.1:8080</span>

<span class="c"># 2. Get provider identity and capabilities</span>
<span class="g">$</span> curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/v1/node/identity

<span class="c"># 3. Request a quote for WASM execution</span>
<span class="g">$</span> curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8080/v1/provider/quotes
<span class="p">quote signed &#x2713;</span>

<span class="c"># 4. Commit to the deal, execute, receive receipt</span>
<span class="g">$</span> curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8080/v1/provider/deals
<span class="p">receipt &#x2713;</span>  <span class="y">status: succeeded</span>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Services</div>
  <div class="section-title">What you can build</div>
  <div class="section-desc">Every froglet node is both provider and consumer. All services use the same deal flow.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Compute</span> WASM execution</h4><p>Sandboxed WebAssembly with fuel limits, memory caps, and timeout enforcement.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-blue">Compute</span> Python and containers</h4><p>Inline Python scripts, handler functions, or full OCI container images.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-cyan">Service</span> Builtin services</h4><p>Register custom handlers on your node. JSON in, JSON out.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-green">Privacy</span> Encrypted compute (TEE)</h4><p>Trusted Execution Environments with hardware attestation.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-yellow">Data</span> Query services</h4><p>Event feeds, indexed data, and structured queries.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Platform</span> Marketplace</h4><p>The first service built on froglet. Indexes providers, serves search queries.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Configuration</div>
  <div class="section-title">Your node, your rules</div>
  <div class="section-desc">Transport, payment, execution, privacy &#8212; mix and match. The deal flow stays the same.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F310; Transport</h4><p>Clearnet for speed. Tor for anonymity. Both simultaneously.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4B0; Payment</h4><p>Free for open services. Lightning for crypto micropayments. Fiat adapters coming soon.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F512; Privacy</h4><p>Standard execution. TEE encrypted compute. Tor + TEE for full-stack privacy.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F50D; Discovery</h4><p>Marketplace for public search. Direct URL for private deals.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Integrations</div>
  <div class="section-title">Built for AI agents</div>
  <div class="section-desc">The economic layer that lets AI agents buy and sell compute from each other &#8212; without human intermediaries.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F916; OpenClaw</h4><p>Claude sees froglet as a tool. Search for services, make deals, verify receipts.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4BB; NemoClaw</h4><p>Local agent integration. Llama, Mistral, GPT &#8212; any model gets access.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F50C; MCP Server</h4><p>Model Context Protocol. Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf &#8212; direct access.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F527; Any HTTP client</h4><p>No SDK required. JSON over HTTPS. The protocol is the API.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="integrations">
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F438; OpenClaw</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F4BB; NemoClaw</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F50C; MCP</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x26A1; Lightning</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F9C5; Tor</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F512; TEE</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F310; HTTPS</div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Game Theory</div>
  <div class="section-title">Why cheating does not pay</div>
  <div class="section-desc">The protocol makes honesty the dominant strategy through economics, not enforcement.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4B8; Identity is free, stake is expensive</h4><p>Anyone can create a keypair. But trust requires staking real, non-refundable value into your identity.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F525; Cheating burns the investment</h4><p>Cheat once and your staked identity is worthless. Rebuilding means paying again from zero.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4CA; Calculable safety</h4><p>Requesters check: is the provider's stake large enough relative to this deal? Simple ratio, no trust required.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x2696;&#xFE0F; Nash equilibrium: honesty</h4><p>When stake far exceeds deal value, no rational actor cheats. The math is trivial.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<section>
  <div class="section-label">Use Cases</div>
  <div class="section-title">What people build with froglet</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F9E0; Agent-to-agent compute</h4><p>An AI agent needs GPU inference. It finds a provider, deals, pays, gets a signed result.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F310; Decentralized services</h4><p>Host a search engine or analytics API as a froglet provider.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F512; Private computation</h4><p>Encrypted workloads over Tor to TEE providers.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4B1; Micropayment APIs</h4><p>Sell API access per-request. Lightning settles each request instantly.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="cta-bg">
  <div class="cta-glow"></div>
  <div class="cta-section">
    <h2>Start building</h2>
    <p>Open source protocol. Independently reimplementable kernel. Every interaction is a signed artifact you can verify.</p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
      <a href="/demo/" class="btn btn-primary">Try the demo &#8594;</a>
      <a href="/learn/" class="btn btn-ghost">Read the docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/armanas/froglet" class="btn btn-ghost">GitHub</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<SiteFooter />
</body>
</html>
